// SOURCE: Source Files/Intergrations/Fusion - Rust Replacements/Fusion Product Sheet- Flux-Resolve v2.0
// NOTE: Integrated into the Fusion FSN tree for migration traceability.
// CONTENT:
// Product Guide: Flux-Resolve v2.0Component ID: F-RESOLVE-V2Classification: Resolution EngineAuthor: Build Engineering Lead1. Vision & PurposeFlux-Resolve v2.0 is the "Time-Travel" resolution layer for the Fusion ecosystem. While standard package managers look forward, v2.0 looks backward into the Merkle-tree of the registry to guarantee that any build from the past remains reproducible regardless of the current state of the internet.2. Technical Replacement SpecsReplacesStandard Rust EquivalentFusion ImplementationSolverCargo PubGrub (SemVer)SAT-based Hash Constraint SolverLockfileCargo.lockMerkle-Registry State TimestampVersioningSemantic Versioning (^1.0)Cryptographic Identity Pinning3. Key Functionspub fn resolve_to_timestamp(ts: Timestamp) -> Result<Graph, Error>Reconstructs the entire dependency tree as it existed at the exact microsecond specified.Mechanism: Queries the immutable Merkle-Registry.Outcome: Zero reliance on a local lockfile; the source of truth is the global state history.pub fn verify_abi_compatibility(a: Crate, b: Crate) -> boolUsed to eliminate diamond dependencies. If two crates request different versions, Flux-Resolve inspects the exposed symbol table and layouts to see if they can be unified without breaking the binary.4. Why this exists"It worked on my machine" is a symptom of unstable resolution. Flux-Resolve v2.0 ensures that if a build passed on Jan 2nd, 2026, it will pass on Jan 2nd, 2036, without a single byte of difference in the binary.
